+#### 7b.1 — Cookbook: GEMM progression from naive to cuBLAS-competitive (5 measured silicon fires)
+
+Five distinct silicon-validated GEMM kernel patterns landed on origin/main between PRs #191 and #213, each strictly more sophisticated than the previous. Each step lists the PR, the kernel shape, the new PTX feature it introduces, the measured falsifier, and the lesson for the next step.
+
+**Step 1 — Single 16x16 WMMA tile** _(PR #191, RFC 067 P4 silicon)_
+- Shape: 16x16 GEMM, one `wmma.mma` call, FP16 inputs, FP32 accumulator
+- New PTX features: `.reg .b32 %fra<id>_e<i>` fragment vectors (8 elements per fragment), `wmma.load.a.row.f16`, `wmma.load.b.col.f16`, `wmma.mma.sync.aligned.row.col.m16n16k16.f32.f16.f16.f32`, `wmma.store.d.f32`
+- Falsifier: `F-RFC067-TILE-LOOP-NUMERIC` — `max|Δ|=0` vs FP32 CPU reference on a single 16x16x16 tile
+- Result: PASS. Confirms the Tensor Core path is reachable from hexa codegen
+- Lesson: Single-tile is the smallest meaningful WMMA test — it exercises fragment register decl, ld/mma/st instructions, and the `.shared` staging buffer in isolation. Use it as a smoke test before larger shapes.
+- **PTX-diff oracle (2026-05-21, RFC 067 P6)**: 40 SASS instr vs nvcc `wmma::fragment` reference's 87 SASS instr (hexa = 53.9% of nvcc); the delta is the `fill_fragment(C, 0.0f)` init that hexa-emit skips by ABI convention. Structural-density data point only — wall-clock at this scale still cuBLAS 2x (PR #214). Artifact: `inbox/fires/rfc067_p6_revalidate_2026_05_21/`
+
+**Step 2 — Multi-K-tile accumulation (64x16x64)** _(PR #205, RFC 067 §3 P4 extension)_
+- Shape: 64x16 output, K-loop with 4 K-tiles (K=64), accumulator carried in C fragment across iterations
+- New PTX features: explicit 4-iteration K-loop with `wmma.load.a`/`wmma.load.b` reissue per iteration; C fragment registers persist (no spill to `.shared` between iterations)
+- Falsifier: `F-RFC067-TILE-LOOP-NUMERIC-MULTI` — `max|Δ|=0` vs FP32 reference on the 64x16x64 problem
+- Result: PASS
+- Lesson: C-fragment register pressure is the binding constraint — at 4 K-tiles, ptxas keeps all 8 C-fragment registers live across the loop; beyond ~8 tiles you spill. This is where loop unrolling (RFC 069 factor=N) starts to interact with WMMA emit.
+
+**Step 3 — Multi-warp grid (16-warp 64x64x16)** _(PR #206, RFC 067 §3 P4 extension)_
+- Shape: 64x64 output tile = 4x4 16x16 WMMA tiles, one warp per output tile (16 warps total per CTA)
+- New PTX features: per-warp `tid.x / 32` discrimination, per-warp `.shared` staging slot offsets, `bar.sync 0` between A/B load and `wmma.mma` issue
+- Falsifier: `F-RFC067-MULTI-WARP-NUMERIC` — `max|Δ|=0` vs FP32 reference on the 64x64x16 problem
+- Result: PASS
+- Lesson: `.shared` slot allocation per warp is the new dimension — 16 warps each need their own A/B staging slots (2 KiB per warp × 16 = 32 KiB, fits in sm_120's 100 KiB per-SM `.shared`). Beyond 16 warps per CTA, occupancy starts depending on `.shared` use rather than register count.
+
+**Step 4 — cp.async pipelined K-loop** _(PR #207, RFC 067 §3 P4 + sm_80 cp.async)_
+- Shape: same 64x16x64 as Step 2, but A/B tiles prefetched via `cp.async.cg.shared.global`
+- New PTX features: `cp.async.commit_group` / `cp.async.wait_group` pipeline barriers, double-buffer `.shared` staging (2 slots alternating fill/use)
+- Falsifier: `F-RFC067-CP-ASYNC-NUMERIC` — `max|Δ|=0` vs Step 2 (no-async) baseline at K=64
+- Result: PASS numerically; perf measurement showed **~7% slower than no-async at K=64** — honest negative perf delta (memory `project_flame_phase4d9_closure` notes this in `5m`)
+- Lesson: `cp.async` overhead amortizes only at large K (≥ 256). For small K, the `cp.async.commit_group`/`wait_group` barriers cost more than the prefetch saves. This is the canonical "instrument-first" failure mode (memory `feedback_instrument_first_methodology`) — measure cheaply before declaring a perf win.
+
+**Step 5 — tf32 path (Ampere+ default-precision GEMM)** _(PR #213, RFC 068 P4 silicon)_
+- Shape: 16x16 GEMM with tf32 inputs (effectively 19-bit mantissa fp32), FP32 accumulator
+- New PTX features: `.reg .b32` (tf32 stored as raw bits, same as f32 container per PTX ISA §5.4), `wmma.mma.sync.aligned.row.col.m16n16k8.f32.tf32.tf32.f32` mnemonic with `.tf32` element-type tag
+- Falsifier: `F-RFC068-NUMERIC-EQ-TF32` — `max|Δ|=0` vs FP32 reference (tf32 truncates 13 mantissa bits, so the byte-eq is over the 19-bit-mantissa-rounded reference)
+- Result: PASS
+- Lesson: tf32 is the cheapest precision-narrowing path — same container width as fp32 (`.b32`), no ld/st storage changes, just an opcode-suffix flip. Use it as the default `f32 @gpu_kernel` GEMM mnemonic on sm_80+ unless `@deterministic` is required.
+
+**Composite measurement** _(PR #214 + #217, this cycle's perf headline)_
+- Shape: M=N=K=256 HGEMM using all of Step 1+2+3 patterns + tf32 (Step 5)
+- Comparison: hexa-emit `4.0960 TFLOPS` vs cuBLAS GemmEx `8.1907 TFLOPS` = **ratio 0.500 ±0.0002** (6-run variance, sub-0.1% std)
+- Result: §10 closure criterion "≥ 50% of cuBLAS HGEMM" MET at this shape
+- Lesson: The composite kernel sits at the 50% cuBLAS-HGEMM ratio at M=N=K=256. cuBLAS's remaining 2× advantage is its k-loop unroll factor (5×, per memory `reference_ptx_diff_perf_oracle`) + ILP scheduling; the hexa codegen has the *structural* path to close this gap (RFC 069 unroll factor=5 + better register allocation) but the data point is single-shape — scale-up to M=N=K=1024+ is pending (§10 unchecked row in §10.1).
+
+#### 7b.2 — How to extend the cookbook with a new step
+
+Use the same 5-field rubric per step:
+1. **Shape** — M, N, K, dtype, register/`.shared` budget
+2. **New PTX features** — opcode constants added to `nvptx_ptx_ops.hexa`, classifier rules added to `nvptx_target.hexa`
+3. **Falsifier** — `F-RFC0XX-<NAME>` with `max|Δ|=0` or named `≤ 1e-2 rel error` tolerance
+4. **Result** — PASS / FAIL with the actual measurement
+5. **Lesson** — the binding constraint that gates the next step
+
+Reference patterns: `inbox/fires/rfc06[7-9]_p4_*/` for raw artifacts; `tool/r06[7-9]_p4*_host.c` for host launchers; `compiler/codegen/nvptx_lower_test.hexa` Case 9-15 for the codegen-side smoke (no silicon required).
 
